              <h3>Key formulas</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">1. Monthly interest rate</p>
                <p>If APR is expressed as a nominal annual rate:</p>
                <p>\[ r_{\text{monthly}} = \frac{\text{APR}}{12} \]</p>
                <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">
                  2. Interest added each month
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Interest} = \text{Balance}_{\text{start}} \times
                  r_{\text{monthly}} \]
                </p>
                <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">3. Balance update</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Balance}_{\text{end}} = \text{Balance}_{\text{start}}
                  + \text{Interest} - \text{Payment} \]
                </p>
                <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">
                  4. Payment for a target payoff time
                </p>
                <p>
                  If you want to pay off a balance \(B\) in \(n\) months at
                  monthly rate \(r\):
                </p>
                <p>\[ \text{Payment} = \frac{B \cdot r}{1 - (1 + r)^{-n}} \]</p>
              </div>

              <h2>Choosing a payoff strategy: avalanche vs snowball</h2>
              <h3>Debt avalanche (mathematically optimal)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Extra money goes to the card with the
                  <strong>highest APR</strong> first.
                </li>
                <li>Minimizes total interest paid.</li>
                <li>Best if you’re motivated by saving the most money.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Debt snowball (behaviorally friendly)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Extra money goes to the card with the
                  <strong>smallest balance</strong> first.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Often gives you a “quick win” as you eliminate small balances
                  early.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Can be easier to stick with if you need more motivation.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p>
                With this calculator you can model both approaches and see the
                difference in payoff time and interest. In many cases, the
                avalanche method saves more interest, but the snowball method
                may help you stay consistent.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips to pay off credit card debt faster</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Stop adding new charges.</strong> A payoff plan only
                  works if the balance is not growing from new spending.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Automate payments.</strong> Set up automatic payments
                  for at least the minimum plus your planned extra amount.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Increase payments with raises or windfalls.</strong>
                  Re‑run the calculator when your income changes and redirect
                  part of the increase to debt.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consider a 0% balance transfer</strong> if you qualify
                  and can pay off the balance before the promo period ends
                  (watch for fees).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Revisit your budget.</strong> Small cuts in
                  discretionary spending can significantly shorten your payoff
                  time.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  APR is assumed constant; in reality, variable rates can change
                  over time.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Interest is modeled with an effective monthly rate; your
                  issuer may use daily compounding and different rounding rules.
                </li>
                <li>
                  The calculator does not include late fees, annual fees, or new
                  purchases.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Results are estimates for planning and education, not a
                  binding quote from any lender.
                </li>
              </ul>
